Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Poland. The Polish authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
For information on how to return to the UK from Poland, see Return to the UK
Entry and borders
Borders have been closed with border controls introduced by the Polish government now extended until 3 May. International flights have been suspended until 9 May. International rail travel is also suspended. These measures may be extended.
If you are a non-Polish national you cannot enter Poland unless you are a:
Spouse, child or individual under the permanent care of a Polish national; or
Holder of a Pole’s Card; or
Holder of the right to permanent or temporary stay in Poland or a work permit holder; or
Foreign national driving a means of transport used for transporting goods; or
Diplomat, consular staff member, representative of an international organisation or a member of their family transiting Poland, leaving a maximum of 24 hours after entry.
You will be required to self-isolate on arrival in Poland for 14 days (unless you are a commercial driver entering Poland for a limited time for the sole purpose of transporting goods). You will be required to download a special “Home Quarantine” app on a smartphone that allows the local authorities to provide information and stay in regular touch during your self-isolation and check you are abiding by the strict quarantine rules. You will also be required to provide information on arrival about your place of stay or address and a telephone number with which you can be contacted regularly during your self-isolation.
Local measures
Most hotels and short term accommodation establishments are closed to new guests from 2 April, with limited exceptions including for business travellers, quarantine cases and students in university accommodation. If your hotel remains open and you checked in on or before 31 March you can continue your stay. Please consult your accommodation provider for more detailed information.
You are only allowed to leave home or your temporary accommodation to go to work, shop for food or medicine, take exercise or to support the elderly and disabled. From 16 April, you must cover your nose and mouth when outside (with a mask or scarf).
Gatherings of more than two people are prohibited. When outside, you should keep a 2 metre distance from others, unless you are a parent with a child under 13 or the carer of a disabled person. Minors under the age of 13 are only allowed to leave home if accompanied by an adult. A limited number of people at any one time are allowed to attend religious services.
Beaches, zoos, parks and playgrounds are closed, as are cinemas, operas, theatres, museums and other cultural venues. From 20 April, National Forests and parks re-opened, though the nose and mouth covering and social distancing rules above apply if you visit them.
Most shops have been closed but grocery shops, pharmacies and banks remain open. The number of customers at any one time has been restricted and you may have to queue outside until others have finished their shopping. You will be required to wear gloves in shops for sanitary reasons. Restaurants, pubs, clubs and casinos are closed but home delivery services are permitted.
Public transport use is limited to 50% of available seating to maintain appropriate distance between passengers.
There are fines between £1000 - £6000 (5000 – 30000 PLN) if you are found breaking these rules.
All schools and universities are closed until 26 April.
The above measures may be extended further, in scope and time, at short notice.
UK nationals living in Poland should note that the Office for Foreigners has put limitations on in-person appointments. If you are a UK national residing in Poland for over three months, and trying to register your stay, please check the guidance on residency during the coronavirus pandemic applicable to UK nationals.
Further information
The Polish National Health Fund 24 hour info line (800 190 590 and press 6) provides English language advice on what steps to take if you are in Poland and suspect you might have coronavirus. You can find more information about cases in Poland on the TravelHealthPro website.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
